return [
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.rjdexplorer.com/cebu-itinerary/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'RJ Dexplorer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Cebu in Four Days: A Calm DIY Plan for First Timers',
        'slug' => 'cebu-four-days-diy-plan-first-timers',
        'excerpt' => 'A practical four-day Cebu route that mixes heritage walking, mountain side trips, and an island day. Built for first-timers who want to move slow but cover ground.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Cebu is one of those Philippine trips where you can land in the morning, drop your bags by lunch, and already be inside a 17th-century chapel by mid-afternoon. The trick is sequencing. Tackle the city first while your legs are fresh, push out to the mountains on day two, and save the island day for last so you can fly home sun-kissed and unhurried.</p><p>This route assumes a morning arrival on day one and a late-night flight out on day four. Tara, here is the plan.</p><h2>Day 1 and 2: City, Heritage, and Mountain Air</h2><p>From Mactan-Cebu airport, take a Grab or a metered taxi straight to your hotel in downtown or uptown Cebu. Drop your bags, eat a quick lechon lunch at Zubuchon or House of Lechon, then start the heritage loop on foot. Magellan\'s Cross, Basilica del Santo Nino, Plaza Sugbo, and Casa Gorordo are walkable from each other. Cap the day at Fort San Pedro before sunset and have dinner at Larsian for barbecue.</p><h3>Day 2: Up to the Hills</h3><p>Book a private driver or join a group van for the Cebu Transcentral Highway loop. The usual stops are Sirao Flower Garden, Temple of Leah, and Tops Lookout for the city view at golden hour. If you have stamina, add Adventure Cafe in Busay. Get back to the city by 8 p.m. for late dinner at AA BBQ in Mango Avenue.</p><h2>Day 3: South or North, Pick One</h2><p>Day three is where Cebu trips usually split. South Cebu gives you Kawasan Falls in Badian and the canyoneering route from Alegria. North Cebu gives you Bantayan or Malapascua if you can spare the ferry hours. For a first visit, south is the sulit pick because you can do it as a long day trip from the city using a hired van.</p><h3>What to Pack for the Day Trip</h3><ul><li>Quick-dry shorts and a rashguard for the falls</li><li>Reef-safe sunscreen</li><li>A dry bag for your phone</li><li>Sandals with a back strap, not slippers</li></ul><p>Leave Cebu City by 4 a.m. if you are doing canyoneering. The Matutinao trailhead is a three-hour drive, and the queue at the jump-off gets long by mid-morning. You will be back in the city by dinner, just enough time to pack and rest.</p><h2>Day 4: Island Day, Then Fly</h2><p>For your last day, head to Mactan and book an island-hopping boat to Nalusuan, Hilutungan, and Caohagan. Most boats leave by 8 a.m. and return by 2 p.m., which leaves you a clean window to shower, eat dinner near the airport, and catch a late flight. If you are not into snorkeling, swap this for a half-day at Kawasan in the south or a Talisay seafood lunch at Sutukil row.</p><h3>Getting Around</h3><p>For city moves, Grab works well. For day trips, hiring a van through your hotel or a verified driver is more efficient than chasing jeepneys. Domestic flights into Mactan-Cebu run hourly from Manila, and <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> usually has the early slots. For listings of where to sleep before you commit, you can cross-check on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g294264-Cebu_Island_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p><h3>Where to Stay</h3><p>Stay in IT Park or Lahug if you want a walkable food scene at night. Stay in Mactan if your priority is the beach and an easy airport run. Avoid splitting your stay across both unless you have five nights or more, because the bridge traffic eats your itinerary.</p><p>Cebu rewards travelers who plan loose. Lock in your flights and the first hotel, leave the rest to the day. Grabe the food alone is worth the trip.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.rjdexplorer.com/cebu-itinerary/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">RJ Dexplorer</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Cebu 4-Day DIY Itinerary for First Timers | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm four-day Cebu plan covering heritage walks, the mountain loop, Kawasan canyoneering, and a Mactan island-hopping finish before your flight home.',
